<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=c3ff2865-c12f-43fd-8ab8-ffb82b5428de">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p>Overall, both datasets come from real-world sources and are likely to contain missing values, inconsistencies, and recording errors. Before any meaningful analysis or machine learning model can be developed, the data must be cleaned, standardized, and validated. Special attention should be given to ensuring that state names and year values are consistent across both datasets so that they can be merged accurately and produce reliable results.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=c9a90b20-6895-4017-966e-f03f75cbfa47">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h1 id="TASK-2-:-MISSING-VALUE-TREATMENT-STRATEGY">TASK 2 : MISSING VALUE TREATMENT STRATEGY<a class="anchor-link" href="#TASK-2-:-MISSING-VALUE-TREATMENT-STRATEGY">¶</a></h1><p>Deleting all rows with nulls risks losing too much data. Filling everything
with the mean ignores column type and distribution. Instead, each column
is treated based on what it represents and how much data is missing.
<strong>Rules applied:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><p>If a column is missing &gt;50% of values → drop the column entirely
(too little real data to impute reliably)</p>
</li>
<li><p>If a numeric column has a skewed distribution → impute with <strong>median</strong>
(mean is pulled by outliers; median is more robust)</p>
</li>
<li><p>If a numeric column is roughly symmetric → impute with <strong>mean</strong></p>
</li>
<li><p>If a categorical column has missing values → impute with <strong>mode</strong>
(most frequent value; mean/median don't apply to text)</p>
</li>
<li><p>If missing values are few (&lt;1%) → drop those rows
(negligible data loss, avoids introducing imputed noise)</p>
<h3 id="Missing-Value-Treatment-Strategy">Missing Value Treatment Strategy<a class="anchor-link" href="#Missing-Value-Treatment-Strategy">¶</a></h3></li>
</ul>
<p>The dataset contains missing values in several columns. A single approach is not suitable for all columns because the amount of missing data and the column type vary.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Columns with more than 50% missing values are dropped because they contain insufficient information for reliable imputation.</p>
</li>
<li><p>If a column has very few missing values (less than 1%), the affected rows are removed because the data loss is negligible.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Numerical columns with skewed distributions are imputed using the median because median is less sensitive to outliers.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Numerical columns with approximately symmetric distributions are imputed using the mean because it represents the central tendency of the data.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Categorical columns are imputed using the mode (most frequent value) because mean and median cannot be applied to text values.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Missing values are checked before and after treatment to verify that the strategy was successful.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div>
