<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=a5ccd862-1509-45d3-9496-cb6796a301d5">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h2 id="Response-to-the-Journalist">Response to the Journalist<a class="anchor-link" href="#Response-to-the-Journalist">¶</a></h2><p>The data shows that air quality in India was at its worst in the
earlier years of this period and has shown some improvement in
more recent years, with the lowest average AQI recorded towards
the end of the dataset. However this improvement is not smooth
or consistent — there are years where pollution went up again
before coming back down. The noticeable drop around 2020 is
likely linked to the COVID-19 lockdowns when factories and
vehicles were largely shut down rather than any government
pollution policy. After activity resumed, AQI rose again before
gradually settling at a slightly lower level. So while the
overall direction looks mildly positive, it is too early to
say the improvement is because of policy — other factors like
lockdowns, rainfall and seasonal variation all play a role
in these numbers.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=de197fde-d83a-43d5-ae04-3a1d7dc1673c">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h2 id="Task-7-%E2%80%94-Seasonal-AQI-Pattern">Task 7 — Seasonal AQI Pattern<a class="anchor-link" href="#Task-7-%E2%80%94-Seasonal-AQI-Pattern">¶</a></h2><p>The NGO says October to December is the worst period for air quality
because farmers burn leftover crop material after harvesting.</p>
<p>I will check this by looking at average AQI for every month of the year.
If the NGO is right, October, November and December should clearly stand
out as the highest bars in the chart.</p>
<p>Why monthly grouping:</p>
<ul>
<li>Monthly is the right level here</li>
<li>Quarterly hides which specific month is the problem</li>
<li>Weekly adds too much noise and no clear seasonal story</li>
<li>Monthly gives 12 clear groups that are easy to compare</li>
</ul>
<p>How I get the month from the date column:</p>
<ul>
<li>The date column is plain text right now</li>
<li>I convert it to a proper date using pd.to_datetime</li>
<li>Then I use .dt.month to extract just the month number</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=c0bf8d6f-6584-473c-b1da-5ae56b343244">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In [87]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
<div class="cm-editor cm-s-jupyter">
<div class="highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pandas</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">pd</span>

<span class="n">aqi</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"city_day.csv"</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">aqi</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'crop_production.csv'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># see exactly what columns exist</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">aqi</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tolist</span><span class="p">())</span>

<span class="c1"># see first 2 rows</span>
