<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=a9f59b26-6181-4965-ad16-67ba1e276e06">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h2 id="Interpretation-for-the-Research-Team">Interpretation for the Research Team<a class="anchor-link" href="#Interpretation-for-the-Research-Team">¶</a></h2><p>The Pearson r value tells us the strength and direction of the
linear relationship between average state AQI and total crop
production.</p>
<p>If r is close to 0:
No meaningful linear relationship exists. The data does not
on its own justify funding a causal study. Other factors like
farm size, rainfall and irrigation are almost certainly driving
production differences far more than air quality.</p>
<p>If r is moderately negative (around -0.3 to -0.6):
A weak inverse pattern exists — more polluted states tend to
produce slightly less. This is worth investigating further but
is not strong enough to prove pollution is the cause.</p>
<p>If r is strongly negative (below -0.7):
A consistent pattern exists across states. Still not proof of
causation but strong enough to justify a controlled field study.</p>
<p>What r cannot tell the research team:
Even a strong r does not prove that pollution reduces yield.
Highly polluted states are often large farming states where
the pollution comes from the farming itself — burning stubble
after harvest. This means pollution and production can move
together or in opposite directions for completely unrelated reasons.</p>
<p>Rainfall, irrigation coverage, soil fertility and government
subsidies all affect production independently of air quality
and none of these variables are in this dataset. The research
team would need a controlled study that holds these factors
fixed before any causal claim can be made responsibly.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=c2035f3e-55d3-4827-b24b-f2a8f2b0f346">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h2 id="Task-C-%E2%80%94-One-Plot-to-Rule-Them-All">Task C — One Plot to Rule Them All<a class="anchor-link" href="#Task-C-%E2%80%94-One-Plot-to-Rule-Them-All">¶</a></h2><p>Chosen visualisation: Task 7 — Average AQI by Month bar chart</p>
<p>Caption:</p>
<p>Every October, November and December without a single exception
across all years in this dataset, India's air quality deteriorates
to its worst levels — precisely when millions of farmers are burning
crop stubble after the kharif harvest, and precisely when farming
families are spending the most time outdoors in their fields.</p>
<p>This chart is the most actionable finding in the entire analysis
because it connects pollution directly to a calendar that a
government can intervene in — stubble management subsidies and
burning restrictions targeted at a specific three month window
could address the spike that no other season comes close to matching.</p>
<p>No other chart in this analysis shows a pattern this consistent,
this repeatable year after year, and this directly tied to a
decision that policymakers can actually make this coming season.</p>
<p>What it cannot show is whether the burning alone or the cold
windless winter air that traps all pollution close to the ground
in the same months is the bigger driver — answering that question
would require field level data on actual burning locations and
wind measurements that this dataset does not contain. Showing that
two things happen at the same time is not the same as proving
one causes the other.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell" id="cell-id=8c41539c-c2f3-4e3c-9e7e-22e0e0cd0511">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In [151]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
<div class="cm-editor cm-s-jupyter">
<div class="highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pandas</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">pd</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>

<span class="n">crop_df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"crop_production.csv"</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">state_area</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crop_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">groupby</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"State_Name"</span><span class="p">)[</span><span class="s2">"Area"</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sum</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="n">top10</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">state_area</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort_values</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ascending</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">bar</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">top10</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">top10</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"Top 10 States by Cultivated Area"</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"State"</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"Total Area"</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xticks</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">rotation</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">45</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell-outputWrapper">
